1.title: Lab Assignment 3: Multispectral Satellite Image Analysis

2.body: The purpose of this lab exercise is to introduce students to multispectral satellite data, image enhancement techniques, and panchromatic sharpening.
2.title: Introduction

3.body: The following materials, combined with your textbook, can be used as background materials and to help in answering the assignment questions. Weng Q. 2012. An Introduction to contemporary remote sensing, Chapters 7 Section 7.3.1.
3.title: Readings and Resources

4.body: IMPORTANT INFORMATION : The computers in the Geography Undergraduate Computing Lab (Hutt 236), have QGIS and WhiteboxTools installed. If you are planning to carry out these assignments on your own computer, then it is important that you have QGIS, with the WhiteboxTools For QGIS toolbox. This software is open-source, freely available, and works on Windows, MacOS, and Linux operating systems. It can be downloaded from the Internet and instructions can be found on the QGIS homepage (link provided above). For instructions on the installation of the WhiteboxTools plugin for QGIS, please see the WhiteboxTools User Manual . In addition to the software, you will need to download the data associated with this lab exercise from the CourseLink page under the Lab 3 directory. The data for this laboratory is quite large and will require substantial data storage. It is advisable that you purchase a USB flash drive to dedicate to this course and to serve as the data backup. It is important that you backup all of the data for the lab assignment.
4.title: Before you begin

5.body: You will hand in a printed report summarizing the answer to each of the questions in the following exercise along with the necessary colour images. For each of the calculations in this lab, be sure to show your intermediate steps, explicitly stating units and any unit conversions.
5.breadcrumbs: What you need to hand in
5.title: What you need to hand in

6.body: Warning, the data that are used in this lab are quite large. Do not try to run this lab on your personal laptop if it does not have sufficient memory, available hard drive space, and processing power. For example, it is unlikely that a MacBook Air would be sufficiently capable to perform the analyses carried out in this lab exercise. If you find yourself in this situation, use the workstations in the undergraduate computing lab instead. YOU MUST DECOMPRESS (UNZIP) THE LAB DATA FILE BEFORE YOU CAN ANALYZE THE IMAGES CONTAINED WITHIN IT. VERY COMMONLY WHEN STUDENTS COMPLAIN ABOUT AN ERROR THAT WHITEBOXTOOLS OR QGIS THROWS, IT IS THE RESULT OF NOT HAVING DECOMPRESSED THE DATA FILE. Open QGIS and display the raster file band2.tif , band3.tif , and band4.tif . These three images comprise three of the available bands within a Landsat 8 data set collected on 2019-10-12. Using the CreateColourComposite tool (available from WhiteboxTools => Image Processing Tools in QGIS), create a true colour composite using RGB = 4 3 2. Be sure to set the Input Opacity Band to nothing and check the Perform balance contrast enhancement? checkbox. Call the output RGB432.tif , being sure to save the file in your lab working directory. 1.1. Overlay the OpenStreetMap layer on the map to get a sense of the geographic location of the image data set. Provide a description of the landscape captured by this multispectral data set in detail. Be sure to identify the relevant features and landmarks. (5 marks; marks will be assigned based on thoroughness and completeness of answers) Notice that the colours within your composite image appear to be somewhat faded and subdued. Use the DirectDecorrelationStretch tool (WhiteboxTools => Image Processing Tools - Image Enhancement) to perform a saturation stretch on your true colour composite image. You may use the default parameter values; call the output file RGB432_dds.tif and be sure to save it in your working directory. 1.2. Describe the impact of the direct decorrelation stretch on the resulting image. For example, does it improve or worsen your ability to distinguish between different land-covers (e.g. crop types) through visual interpretation of the image? Provide screenshots of detailed (zoomed-in) portions of the study site to justify your answer. (5 marks) 1.3. In your own words, how does this tool operate to enhance the colour of images? That is, how does direct decorrelation stretching work? (3 marks) Now use the UnsharpMasking tool (WhiteboxTools => Image Processing Tools - Filters). Despite the counter-intuitive name of this operation, unsharp masking is used to enhance the sharpness of edges within an image. Again, you may use the default parameters, specifying the input image as RGB432_dds.tif and naming the output RGB432_unsharp.tif . 1.4. What is the purpose of performing edge enhancement on an image? (2 marks) 1.5. Describe the impact that the UnsharpMasking tool has on features within 1) the urban areas (e.g. Fresno, Clovis, and Madera), 2) the agricultural areas (e.g. the areas surrounding the urban centers towards the bottom of the scene), and 3) in the foothill and mountain regions. Provide screenshots of detailed (zoomed-in) portions of the study site to justify your answers. (6 marks; marks will be assigned based on thoroughness and completeness of answers.) Now display the band8.tif image. Zoom into the scene and compare the level of detail provided in this image compared with that of the colour composite image output from the unsharp masking tool. 1.6. Using the information within the 'Layer Properties', how does the spatial resolution of this band 8 image compare with the resolution of the other bands within multispectral data set that you have been provided? What is this band? (2 marks) Use the PanchromaticSharpening tool (WhiteboxTools => Image Processing Tools - Image Enhancement) to combine the band 8 data with the RGB432_unsharp.tif colour composite image. Do not specify the red, green, or blue bands (i.e. remove any auto-populated files names that have been placed in the first three parameters in the PanchromaticSharpening dialog) and specify RGB432_unsharp.tif as the input colour composite image. You may use the default Brovey pan-sharpening method; call the output image pansharp.tif . You will undoubtedly notice that the output of the operation produces an image that is very dark, with an unsatisfactory colour-balance. Use the BalanceContrastEnhancement tool (WhiteboxTools => Image Processing Tools - Image Enhancement) to improve the quality of the pan-sharpened image. Call the output pansharp_bce.tif . 1.7. Provide screenshot comparisons between the original colour composite image ( RGB432_unsharp.tif ) and the pan-sharpened image ( pansharp_bce.tif ) under varying land-cover/land-use (e.g. urban, agricultural, foothills, and mountainous landscapes). (4 marks) 1.8. To what extent has the pan-sharpening operation improved the level of detail in the colour composite image? Provide examples to help justify your answer. (3 marks)
6.title: Enhancing Multispectral Satellite Images

7.body: Mono Lake is the largest waterbody within the Landsat scene. 2.1. Find Mono Lake within the pansharp_bce.tif image and describe the appearance of this waterbody relative to other lakes within the scene. (2 marks) Overlay the Lakes_points.shp vector onto the pan-sharpened image. Notice that Mono Lake corresponds with point 1 in the vector and that two other, more typical lakes within the site are also identified. Now use the ImageStackProfile tool (WhiteboxTools => Image Processing Tools) to generate a type of spectral signature for the three lakes within the points vector file. Specify bands 1-7 as the input files for the analysis and call the output file Lakes_signatures.html , being sure to save it in your Lab 3 working directory. The tool produces an HTML report, including a graph displaying the digital number (i.e. relative brightness) of the corresponding three pixels in each of the specified bands. In truth, for this 'image stack' graph to be a true spectral signature, the bands would need to be transformed into reflectance values instead of simple digital numbers (you may do this in GEOG3420). Also, the x-axis of our graph merely lists the band number rather than the actual wavelength, and this fact would likely change the shape of the three line signatures in the plot. However, this image stack is a useful means of interrogating the relative brightness of different sites and land-covers within a multispectral data set. 2.2. Provide a screenshot of the image stack plot output by the ImageStackProfile tool. (1 mark) 2.3. Does the unique appearance of Lake Mono in the pan-sharpened colour composite have an apparent basis in the spectral signature of this lake relative to the other two? Provide a details justifying your answer. (2 marks) 2.4. What do you think may have caused this unique characteristic of the lake? (hint, do some online research before attempting to answer this question) (3 marks) Overlay the Farm_points.shp vector layer and zoom to the layer extent (right-click over it in the the layers tab and select 'zoom to layer'). You will notice that I have highlighted central pixels within five different agricultural fields west of Fresno. The five sites represent different crop types as well as a fallow field (Point 5). Generate the image stack profile for the five farm sites. 2.5. Provide a screenshot of the image stack plot output by the ImageStackProfile tool applied to the five farm sites. (1 mark) 2.6. Does the general shape of the these profiles (particularly the non-fallow sites), follow the general pattern of the vegetation spectral signature that we have referred to numerous times within lecture? Provide evidence of your understanding by referring to various band numbers and their corresponding spectral regions (e.g. blue, green, red, NIR, etc.). (4 marks) 2.7. Why do you think that Point 4's profile is so different from the others? To answer this question, examine the field in which Point 4 is located within the pan-sharpened colour composite image and consider the time of year. (2 marks)
7.title: Exploring Spectral Signatures
